old</i> (a compound name with the same first element + <i>bald</i> ‘bold, brave’).","German, Dutch, and Danish (of German origin): nickname for a busy or bustling person, from Middle High German <i>hummel</i>, Middle Dutch <i>hommel</i> ‘bee’, of imitative origin. Compare English <i>humblebee</i>, which in modern English has become <i>bumblebee</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Hommet was christened in France. He married Lucy de Brus in 1154, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 6 sons and 2 daughters. He died in Stamford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1135–1190":"1135–1190","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","–1224":"–1224","1160–1224":"1160–1224","1164–1199":"1164–1199","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1168–Male":"1168–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1171–Male":"1171–Surnud","1172–1211":"1172–1211","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1190":"1190","1154":"1154","1164":"1164","1152":"1152","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","1224":"1224","1168":"1168","1135":"1135","1178":"1178","1211":"1211","1166":"1166","1199":"1199","ABT1164":"umbes 1164","ABT1178":"umbes 1178","Stamford, Lincolnshire, England":"Stamford, Lincolnshir